title: ‘Portal to space’: the place where astronauts take off and land – in pictures
description: Every three months in Kazakhstan, a trio of cosmonauts and astronauts head off to the International Space Station – then return in small capsules. What do the locals make of it? Continue reading...
author: Guardian Staff

title: Female astronaut goes to space but can’t escape online sexism by ‘small men’
description: Video posted by Emily Calandrelli about awesome view of Earth was flooded with hateful, objectifying commentsThere isn’t a galaxy far, far away enough where women can escape sexist online trolls.Emily Calandrelli became the 100th woman to go to space when she joined a group of six space tourists in a launch led by Blue Origin, the aerospace company owned by the billionaire Jeff Bezos. Continue reading...
author: Erum Salam

title: John Herrington Performs a Spacewalk
description: On Nov. 30, 2002, NASA astronauts John Herrington (pictured) and Michael Lopez-Alegria performed the third and final spacewalk of the STS-113 mission. author: Monika Luabeya

title: NASA Plane Supported Innovative Microgravity Research in ‘90s
description: A bell rings and a strobe light flashes as a pilot pulls the nose of the DC-9 aircraft up sharply. The blood quickly drains from researchers’ heads as they are pulled to the cabin floor by a force twice that of normal gravity. author: Robert S. Arrighi

title: NASA's Europa Clipper probe deploys 1st science instruments en route to Jupiter
description: NASA's Europa Clipper mission has successfully deployed its magnetometer's boom and several antennas for its radar instrument as it continues on its journey toward Jupiter's ice-covered moon.

title: Japan's priceless asteroid Ryugu sample got 'rapidly colonized' by Earth bacteria
description: A sample of the asteroid Ryugu returned to Earth by the Hayabusa2 mission was rapidly colonized by terrestrial microorganisms, new research has revealed.

title: Super-bright black holes could reveal if the universe is pixelated
description: Space-time may not be continuous but instead made up of many discrete bits – and we may be able to see their effects near the edges of unusually bright black holes

title: Exploding interstellar space rocks could explain mystery radio flashes
description: Enigmatic phenomena called fast radio bursts might be caused by interstellar objects colliding with highly magnetised neutron stars
